abstract: CHICAGO, April 6. -- The election of Tuesday proved several things. One of them was that 32 per cent. of the registered voters concluded not to cast their ballots for either candidate. It was one of the lightest votes cast for many years. Dissatisfaction with Mayor Harrison and Judge Hanecy was the cause, although the latter, in speaking of his defeat, said that he attributed it to the thin shoes worn by so many Republicans.

abstract: CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va., April 8 -- University of Virginia's baseball team met its first defeat of the season here this afternoon, losing to Yale by a score of 9 to 6. abstract: NICE, April 9. -- It was announced here this morning that the Russian squadron was about to arrive at Villefranche, and the news aroused great enthusiasm. Big crowds went to welcome the Russians. abstract: A general recovery from the declines of the previous day occurred yesterday in the market for outside securities. abstract: WASHINGTON, April 11. -- There was interesting sport at Bennings to-day. The weather was delightful, and the crowd very large. Outsiders landed first money in four of the events and only one favorite, The Rogue in the fifth race, won. From a field of sixteen starters False Alarm, at 10 to 1 took the first race, a head in front of Brahmin, who was two lengths in front of the favorite.

abstract: Harry Pipp, thirty-eight years old, keeps a roadhouse at Unionport Road and Morris Park Avenue, Westchester. He had a wife about thirty-five years old, of whom he was very jealous and on whom he had kept a strict watch of late. They lived next door to, the roadhouse. He had been drinking when he went into his house from his bar-room at 11:30 o'clock last night.

abstract: In 1794 M. Chappe set up the first telegraph, of his own devising, at Paris. It was on the roof of the Louvre, and consisted of an upright post with a long crossbar pivoted at the top. abstract: The prices of Baku petroleum, ostatki, and mazoot -- mazoot is the refuse used in furnaces in lieu of coal -- have gone up simply because certain foreign shareholders were bent on raising them artificially. abstract: CHESTER, Mass., April 21 -- The Flood Hollow dam in Middlefield gave way about 6 o'clock to-night, letting loose the water in the big reservoir, which rushed with terrific force into the west branch of the Westfield River, sweeping everything before it and submerging the greater part of this town. abstract: ALBANY, April 23. -- Both branches of the Legislature adjourned sine die this afternoon, the Senate at 12:45 and the Assembly at 1:02 o'clock. Contrary to the custom which has been in vogue for many years, there were no presentations either in the Assembly or the Senate. The customary social features were absent in both houses.

abstract: In the following list "mtg" stands for mortgage and "R S" for revenue stamps. abstract: BOSTON, Mass., April 27. -- The tone of the money market is slightly easier, though Boston rates have not yet changed. On call money ranges from 3 1/2 to 4 1/2 per cent., mostly at 4 per cent. Time money is quoted from 3 3/4 to 4 1/2 per cent, for four to six months and 3 3/4 to 4 per cent for a year. Business paper sells from 4 to 5 per cent.

abstract: MATAWAN, N.J., April 27. -- In a little hut in the woods near Union Hill, where he had lived the life of a hermit for thirty years, Joshua Smith was found starving to death yesterday by the Overseers of the Poor of Marlborough Township. abstract: The Poles have no dealings with the Germans, who in consequence feel supremely uncomfortable in the province and never permanently settle there. Their little world is a world only of public officers, a foreign garrison. The Poles decline to take part in anything which recognizes German rule. abstract: In a loosely played same of baseball yesterday Princeton beat Manhattan at Jasper Field by the score of 16 to 12. The spirit of rivalry was very keen during the contest, for Princeton in a former encounter had defeated Manhattan, 5 to 4. abstract: BERLIN, April 28. -- The money market now shows greater ease than it has shown for several years. abstract: PEKING, April 29. -- The Generals of the powers held a conference this morning to consider the question of the withdrawal of the troops. They decided to address a note to the Ministers, informing them that, when the Ministers are able to announce the lump sum demanded as indemnity and the Chinese have agreed to the principle of payment, arrangements will he possible for withdrawal.
